    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-08-06T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-08-06T15:00:00-05:00" n="398"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d398">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.6363/1918: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sheffield</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-08-06T13:00:00-07:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 6, 1926—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 7—12:38 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>329. Embassy’s despatch No. 2474, July l.<note n="68" xml:id="d398fn68">Not
                        printed; it transmitted the translation of a memorandum left with the
                        Secretary of Industry, Commerce, and Labor by the Oil Producers’ Association
                        on June 24, 1926.</note> I have been informed by representatives of two of
                    the leading British oil companies that they are presenting a modified memorandum
                    to the Mexican Department of Industry regarding the drilling permit order of
                    June 8. They have been given to understand that the memorandum will be accepted
                    and if so the order of June 8 will be virtually nullified. They believe that
                    this changed attitude is due to the firm position assumed in our notes of June
                    22 and July 21.<note n="69" xml:id="d398fn69">Neither printed; for instructions
                        upon which they were based, see telegrams No. 212, June 21, and No. 241,
                        July 20, to the Ambassador in Mexico, <ref target="#pg_679">pp. 679</ref>
                        and <ref target="#pg_680">680</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Despatch will go forward in today’s pouch.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sheffield</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
